\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of assuming that conspicuous consumption is limited to the rich
 and that the poor emulate unconditionally emulate them, we argue that the
 role of reference group is key to the idea of conspicuous consumption.
 Here, a conspicuous item either helps distance oneself from the others
 or provides a satisfaction of having achieved at least as much as others
 in the group - consequences that can be defined only with respect to a
 point of reference.
 In other words, the poor do not unconditionally emulate the rich but instead
 compare themselves to a particular reference point.
 There raises two important questions which we're interested in.
 First, how does this reference point come about? Second, would someone
 in a poorer position benefit from a lowered status consumption? In other
 words, when does emulating the rich start to pay off? We have attempted
 to provide normative answers to these questions using a model of consumption
 where the consumer optimises expected relative wealth relative to a reference
 level.
\end_layout

