\begin_layout Standard
The notion of status in the model used in the current chapter uses both
 reference levels and risk -aversion levels.
 All consumers are set to optimise a private view of status - which is limited
 to a particular reference group from the wider notion of status- that latter
 being independent of how status may be perceived from within a reference
 group.
 What status means to an individual therefore differs from what it may mean
 for the group of individuals viewed at a higher level.
 While a high-status individual in one localised context is not necessarily
 of high-status in another, the notions of power and net-asset-worth are
 certainly shared across multiple contexts (societies, communities, nations
 etc.).
 More formally, in groups 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{i}\}_{i\in[1,m]}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{i\in[1,m]}$
\end_inset

 consumers in each group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

, each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{m}n_{i}$
\end_inset

consumers may have a private view of status, but the notion of we associate
 with each group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

is associated most certainly with the net wealth the group has amassed.
 So while status at personal level might be subject to subjective uncertainties
 that are characteristic of the group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 the status at higher levels is indicated primarily by the material significance
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

 (that determine the reference level for the group 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{i}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

