 and uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a canonical formulation, we use a Bernoulli random process 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $E(W)=p$
\end_inset

) that affects all individuals in the economy.
 The macroeconomic changes in an economy e.g.
 the proliferation of new occupations, onslaught of calamities, rise of
 urbanisation, economic shocks and bubbles or political risks are summarised
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

.
 The gains and losses to an individual economy are represented as a repeated
 lottery to be played by the consumers as they observe the macroeconomic
 events simultaneously.
 The uncertain consumers must decide to position themselves to benefit from
 gains in the economy or to seek protection from any losses that the economy
 is exposed to.
 Given a disposable income 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 - which we define as the the consumer's expenditure after deducting the
 cost of her needs - a consumer can spend an amount 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 towards the upside risk (probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

) to be compensated 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi+P(\nu)$
\end_inset

 in a favourable enviroment as well as pay 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\xi)-\phi$
\end_inset

 in an unfavourable environment (i.e.
 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-p$
\end_inset

) .
 The disposable income are meant to be distributed across the population
 with a known distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The lottery scheme in our binary growth economy is demonstrated in Figure
 
