\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The decisions on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=x-\nu$
\end_inset

 given an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

) depends on the consumer's perceived uncertainty i.e.
 her reference level and risk-aversion.
 As noted before, the total outlay 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (the disposable income) is assumed to randomly distributed in the population.
 In a more general setting, one could consider the returns from consumer's
 investments 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 to be stochastic as well - but in this canonical form we assume that the
 consumer may choose to spread her disposable income between competitive
 and cooperative investments that are rewarded through deterministic functions
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S(\xi)$
\end_inset

 respectively
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size normal
In a real world setting, both the size of of fluctuations and the likelihood
 of return from the individual status item matter to how disposable income
 is spread between upside risk and downturn security.
 For example, with small fluctuations in the market, items of luxury (such
 as jewelry) do offer some security since they can be sold to someone else.
 But on the other hand, the owner of a luxury condominium may find poor
 return (if being able to sell at all) in a market affected by an extreme
 event.
 Similarly, the consumers may spend differently on basic education (which
 offers protection with a high probability) from higher education (which
 may offer high return with a small probability).
 That the consumers respond to an event 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 which has Bernoulli probability is evident simplification of competitions
 for relative wealth.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
