\begin_layout Standard
The two conditions in the game are 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot P(\nu)+(1-p)S(x-\nu)+\{p\chi+(1-p)\phi\}>x$
\end_inset

 at all times for all consumers and that 
\begin_inset Formula $L'>0$
\end_inset

 at all times.
 The former condition can be easily broken if the consumer does gain enough
 relative to the reference point - recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is chosen by maximising utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x,\nu,\alpha)=w(p,\alpha)\upsilon(P(\nu)+\chi-r)+w(1-p,\alpha)\upsilon(S(x-\nu)-\phi-r)$
\end_inset

.
 In a low 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 environment the consumer who is too risk-seeking would continue to lose
 - that means the interest-condition would not be met for her.
 The lottery maker cannot control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 nor can she allocate anything based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 - all what she can do is to ascertain that the risk-seeking consumer does
 not take too much risk - in another words adjust provide more security
 (to incentivise risk-aversion).
 For setting one value for the entire game she would need to choose 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 that considers this possibility.
 Notice that too much risk-aversion in the low 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 environment could also be problematic for the lottery maker because that
 would mean just security investments and too much cash - which is not lottery
 makers intention.
 Since the lottery maker does not observe 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 - she can only ensure that the outliers are not that many i.e.
 the difference in risk-aversion does not cause the income differences so
 much that the reference points makes the lottery worthless.
 She therefore sets up 
\begin_inset Formula $P,S$
\end_inset

 so that outliers are limited or indeed zero.
 The lottery maker only needs to check the sums 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{P}=\sum_{i}^{n}P(\nu_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{S}=\sum_{i}^{n}S(\xi_{i})$
\end_inset

 to see which side is dominates.
 The question is easily answered if we consider how lottery maker balance
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
