 accounts to begin with.
 She cannot afford to keep it anything else but align it with 
\begin_inset Formula $L=p\chi-(1-p)\phi$
\end_inset

.
 The next argument must be made to justify why lottery-maker's amount becomes
 the reference point.
 But considering the primeval problem, how exactly must the lottery maker
 balance her game.
 The truth is the lottery maker is also taking a bet - and she must maximise
 her returns - but in our cases, this a particularly benign lottery maker
 who steps in only to motivate the participants.
 Consider what would happen if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{P}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{S}=0$
\end_inset

 in a low 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 environment i.e.
 all consumers want upside risks.
 The lottery maker is fine as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{P<}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $nL$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the amount to be paid back does not exceed here expected amount.
 Similarly, she must also ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{S}<L$
\end_inset

.
 Combining both arguments we can say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{P-S}<nL$
\end_inset

.
 To double check, consider what would happen if nobody had any income 
\begin_inset Formula $P(\nu)=S(\xi)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The consumers would not be interested in playing the lottery and the 
\begin_inset Formula $nL$
\end_inset

